<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "Is it better to lease or buy a car?", answer: "It depends on your driving habits, financial situation, and preferences. Buying is generally cheaper in the long run because you build equity and can drive the car for years after the loan is paid off. Leasing offers lower monthly payments and lets you drive a new car every few years, but you never own the vehicle and may face mileage penalties. This calculator helps you compare the total cost of each option for your specific situation." },
  { question: "How does resale value affect the lease vs buy comparison?", answer: "Resale value significantly impacts the buy scenario. When you buy a car, you can sell it or trade it in when you are done with it, offsetting a portion of the total cost. A car with strong resale value (like many Toyota or Honda models) makes buying more attractive. A car that depreciates rapidly (like many luxury vehicles) may make leasing the smarter financial choice since the lessor absorbs the depreciation risk." },
  { question: "What are the hidden costs of leasing a car?", answer: "Leasing has several costs beyond the monthly payment: acquisition fees, disposition fees when returning the vehicle, excess mileage charges (typically $0.15 to $0.25 per mile over the limit), wear-and-tear charges for damage beyond normal use, and gap insurance. You also pay for maintenance on a car you will never own. These costs can add thousands to the total lease expense." },
  { question: "How long should I keep a car to make buying worthwhile?", answer: "Generally, buying becomes more cost-effective when you keep the car for at least 5 to 7 years. After the loan is paid off (typically 5 to 6 years), you have no monthly payments while continuing to drive the car. The longer you keep it beyond the loan payoff, the lower your average monthly cost of ownership becomes. If you prefer driving a new car every 2 to 3 years, leasing may be more practical." },
  { question: "What is the total cost of buying a car?", answer: "The total cost includes the down payment, all monthly loan payments (principal plus interest), insurance, maintenance, and repairs. To get the net cost, subtract the estimated resale value when you eventually sell or trade in the vehicle. This calculator computes the total loan cost including your down payment and interest, minus the resale value, for a clear comparison against leasing." }
]) %>

